&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;1.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt; &lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Operations and Summary of Significant Accounting Policies&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Description of Business&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Inventure Foods
&amp;#160;Inc.
 a Delaware corporation (referred to herein as the &amp;#8220;Company
&amp;#8221; referred to as &amp;#8220;we
&amp;#8221; &amp;#8220;our&amp;#8221; or &amp;#8220;us&amp;#8221;)
 is a leading marketer and manufacturer of healthy/natural and indulgent specialty snack food brands with more than $215 million in annual net revenues for fiscal year 2013.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We operate in two segments: frozen products and snack products. The frozen products segment produces frozen fruits
 vegetables and beverages for sale primarily to groceries
 club stores and mass merchandisers.&amp;#160; All products sold under our frozen products segment are considered part of the healthy/natural food category.&amp;#160; The snack products segment produces potato chips
 kettle chips
 potato crisps
 potato skins
 pellet snacks
 sheeted dough products and extruded products for sale primarily to snack food distributors and retailers.&amp;#160; The products sold under our snack products segment includes products considered part of the indulgent specialty snack food category
 as well as products considered part of the healthy/natural food category.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We specialize in two primary product categories: (1)&amp;#160;healthy/natural food products (2)&amp;#160;indulgent specialty snack products.&amp;#160; We sell our products nationally through a number of channels including: grocery
 natural
 mass merchandisers
 drug
 club
 value
 vending
 food service
 convenience stores and international.&amp;#160; Our goal is to have a diversified portfolio of brands
 products
 customers and distribution channels.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;In our healthy/natural food category
 products include Rader Farms&amp;#174; frozen berries
 Boulder Canyon&amp;#174; Natural Foods brand kettle cooked potato chips
 Willamette Valley Fruit Company&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=POSITION: relative; FONT-SIZE: 6.5pt; TOP: -3pt; size=1&gt;TM&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;&amp;#160;brand frozen berries
 Fresh Frozen&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=POSITION: relative; FONT-SIZE: 6.5pt; TOP: -3pt; size=1&gt;TM&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;&amp;#160;brand frozen vegetables
 Jamba&amp;#174; branded blend-and-serve smoothie kits under license from Jamba Juice Company
 Seattle&amp;#8217;s Best Coffee&amp;#174; Frozen Coffee Blends branded blend-and-serve frozen coffee beverage under license from Seattle&amp;#8217;s Best Coffee
 LLC and private label frozen fruit and healthy/natural snacks.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;In our indulgent specialty snack food category
 products include T.G.I. Friday&amp;#8217;s&amp;#174; brand snacks under license from T.G.I. Friday&amp;#8217;s Inc. (&amp;#8220;T.G.I. Friday&amp;#8217;s&amp;#8221;)
 Nathan&amp;#8217;s Famous&amp;#174; brand snack products under license from Nathan&amp;#8217;s Famous Corporation
 Vidalia&amp;#174; brand snack products under license from Vidalia Brands
&amp;#160;Inc.
 Poore Brothers&amp;#174; kettle cooked potato chips
 Bob&amp;#8217;s Texas Style&amp;#174; kettle cooked chips
 and Tato Skins&amp;#174; brand potato snacks.&amp;#160; We also manufacture private label snacks for certain grocery retail chains and co-pack products for other snack and cereal manufacturers.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We operate manufacturing facilities in seven locations.&amp;#160; Our frozen berry products are manufactured in Lynden
 Washington and two facilities in Salem
 Oregon.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Our frozen berry business grows
 processes and markets premium berry blends
 raspberries
 blueberries and rhubarb and purchases marionberries
 cherries
 cranberries
 strawberries and other fruits from a select network of fruit growers for resale.&amp;#160; The fruit is processed
 frozen and packaged for sale and distribution to wholesale customers.&amp;#160; Our frozen vegetable products are manufactured in Jefferson
 Georgia and Thomasville
 Georgia.&amp;#160; Our frozen beverage products are packaged at our Lynden
 Washington facility.&amp;#160; We also use third-party processors for certain frozen products and package certain frozen fruits for other manufacturers.&amp;#160; Our snack products are manufactured at our Phoenix
 Arizona and Bluffton
&amp;#160;Indiana plants
 as well as some third-party plants for certain products.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Acquisitions and Dispositions&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We account for acquisitions using the acquisition method of accounting.&amp;#160; The results of operations of our acquired businesses have been included in our consolidated results from their respective dates of acquisition.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;On November&amp;#160;8
 2013
 we completed our acquisition of Fresh Frozen Foods
 LLC (&amp;#8220;Fresh Frozen Foods&amp;#8221;) for a cash purchase price of $38.4 million plus a working capital adjustment of $0.4 million.&amp;#160; An additional amount of up to $3.0 million is payable to Fresh Frozen Foods as contingent consideration in the form of an earn-out based on 2014 performance (see Note 2).&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;On May&amp;#160;28
 2013
 we completed our acquisition of the berry processing business of Willamette Valley Fruit Company
 LLC (&amp;#8220;Willamette Valley Fruit Company&amp;#8221;) for a cash purchase price of $9.3 million.&amp;#160; An additional amount of up to $3.0 million is payable to Willamette Valley Fruit Company as contingent consideration in the form of an earn-out if certain performance thresholds are met during the seven-year period following the closing of the transaction (see Note 2).&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;On November 5
 2012
 we sold our direct-store-delivery (&amp;#8220;DSD&amp;#8221;) business for $1.2 million in cash
 which included a network of independently operated and owned service routes and limited fixed assets associated with the DSD business.&amp;#160; We received an additional $0.3 million as a purchase price adjustment for inventory on-hand.&amp;#160; We recognized a net gain of $1.1 million in continuing operations
 as we will continue to indirectly sell our products through this network at a reduced cost and will no longer sell distributed products.&amp;#160; Our sales of distributed products were $2.6 million in fiscal year 2012.&amp;#160; Our DSD business was part of our indulgent specialty snack segment and included a limited number of snack food products purchased and sold through our DSD network in Arizona.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Principles of Consolidation&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of Inventure Foods
&amp;#160;Inc. and all of its wholly owned subsidiaries.&amp;#160; All significant intercompany amounts and transactions have been eliminated.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Our fiscal year ends on the last Saturday occurring in the month of December&amp;#160;of each calendar year.&amp;#160; Accordingly
 the fiscal year end dates result in an additional week of results every five or six years.&amp;#160; Fiscal year 2013 commenced December&amp;#160;30
 2012 and ended December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 resulting in a 52-week fiscal year.&amp;#160; Fiscal year 2012 commenced January&amp;#160;1
 2012 ended December&amp;#160;29
 2012
 resulting in a 52-week fiscal year.&amp;#160; Fiscal year 2011 commenced December&amp;#160;26
 2010 ended December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 resulting in a 53-week fiscal year.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Use of Estimates&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;The preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&amp;#8220;GAAP&amp;#8221;) requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities
 disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements
 and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period.&amp;#160; We routinely evaluate our estimates
 including those related to accruals for customer programs and incentives
 product returns
 bad debts
 income taxes
 long-lived assets
 inventories
 stock-based compensation
 interest rate swap valuations
 accrued broker commissions and contingencies.&amp;#160; We base our estimates on historical experience and on various other assumptions that are believed to be reasonable under the circumstances.&amp;#160; Actual results could differ from those estimates.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Fair Value of Financial Instruments&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.4in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Fair value is defined as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability (i.e.
 the &amp;#8220;exit price&amp;#8221;) in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date.&amp;#160; W&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;e classify our investments based upon an established fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the inputs to valuation techniques used to measure fair value.&amp;#160; The hierarchy gives the highest priority to unadjusted quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities (Level 1 measurement) and the lowest priority to unobservable inputs (Level 3 measurement).&amp;#160; The three levels of the fair value hierarchy are described as follows:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.4in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table style=text-align:left;WIDTH: 94.66%; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; MARGIN-LEFT: 0.4in; border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=94%&gt;
&lt;tr style=padding:0;&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 9.06%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=top width=9%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Level 1&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.34%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 89.62%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=top width=89%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Unadjusted quoted prices in active markets that are accessible at the measurement date for identical
 unrestricted assets or liabilities.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=padding:0;&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 9.06%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=top width=9%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.34%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 89.62%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=top width=89%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=padding:0;&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 9.06%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=top width=9%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Level 2&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.34%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 89.62%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=top width=89%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Quoted prices in markets that are not considered to be active or financial instruments without quoted market prices
 but for which all significant inputs are observable
 either directly or indirectly.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=padding:0;&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 9.06%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=top width=9%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.34%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 89.62%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=top width=89%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr style=padding:0;&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 9.06%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=top width=9%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Level 3&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.34%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 89.62%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=top width=89%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Prices or valuations that require inputs that are both significant to the fair value measurement and unobservable.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: -1in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 1.4in;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.4in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;A financial instrument&amp;#8217;s level within the fair value hierarchy is based on the lowest level of any input that is significant to the fair value measurement.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;At December&amp;#160;28
 2013 and December&amp;#160;29
 2012
 the carrying value of cash
 accounts receivable
 accounts payable and accrued liabilities approximate fair values since they are short term in nature.&amp;#160; The carrying value of the long-term debt approximates fair value based on the borrowing rates currently available to us for long-term borrowings with similar terms. The following table summarized the valuation of our assets and liabilities measured at fair value on a recurring basis (in thousands):&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 8.7%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=8%&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: right; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;&amp;#8212;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=1%&gt;

&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Considerable judgment is required in interpreting market data to develop the estimate of fair value of our derivative instruments.&amp;#160; Accordingly
 the estimate may not be indicative of the amounts that we could realize in a current market exchange.&amp;#160; The use of different market assumptions or valuation methodologies could have a material effect on the estimated fair value amounts.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Our non-qualified deferred compensation plan assets consist of money market and mutual funds invested in domestic and international marketable securities that are directly observable in active markets.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;The fair value measurement of the earn-out contingent consideration obligation relates to the acquisition of Willamette Valley Fruit Company in May&amp;#160;2013 and Fresh Frozen Foods in November&amp;#160;2013
 and is included in accrued liabilities and other long-term liabilities in the consolidated balance sheets.&amp;#160; The fair value measurement is based upon significant inputs not observable in the market.&amp;#160; Changes in the value of the obligation are recorded as income or expense in our consolidated statements of income.&amp;#160; We estimated the original fair value of the contingent consideration as the present value of the expected contingent payments
 determined using the weighted probabilities of the possible payments.&amp;#160; We are required to reassess the fair value of the contingent payments on a contingent basis.&amp;#160; Significant increases (decreases) in any of those probabilities in isolation may result in a higher (lower) fair value measurement.&amp;#160; The significant inputs used in these estimates include numerous possible scenarios for the payments based on the contractual terms of the contingent consideration
 for which probabilities are assigned to each scenario
 which are then discounted based on an individual risk analysis of the respective liabilities (weighted average discount rate of 5.4% for the outstanding liabilities as of December&amp;#160;28
 2013).&amp;#160; Although we believe our assumptions are reasonable
 different assumptions or changes in the future may result in different estimated amounts.&amp;#160; A one percentage point change in the discount rates used would not have significantly impacted the recorded liability as of December&amp;#160;28
 2013.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;A summary of the activity of the fair value of the measurements using unobservable inputs (Level 3 Liabilities) for the year ended December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 is as follows (in thousands):&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: -10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Earn-out compensation due to Fresh Frozen Foods&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;

&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: right; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;2

&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.36%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=1%&gt;

&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: -10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 10pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Balance at December&amp;#160;28
 2013&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 3.4%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=bottom width=3%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.3%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: medium none; BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 15.06%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BORDER-TOP: windowtext 1pt solid; BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=bottom width=15%&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: right; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;5
053&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.36%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Derivative Financial Instruments&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We utilize interest rate swaps in the management of our variable interest rate exposure and do not enter into derivatives for trading purposes.&amp;#160; All derivatives are measured at fair value.&amp;#160; Our interest rate swaps are classified as cash flow hedges.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Treasury Stock&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We record repurchases of our Common stock
 $.01 par value (&amp;#8220;Common Stock&amp;#8221;)
 as treasury stock at cost.&amp;#160; We also record the subsequent retirement of these treasury shares at cost.&amp;#160; The excess of the cost of the shares retired over their par value is allocated between additional paid-in capital and retained earnings.&amp;#160; The amount recorded as a reduction of paid-in capital is based on such excess.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Cash and Cash Equivalents&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We consider all highly liquid investments purchased with an original maturity of three months or less to be cash equivalents.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Accounts Receivable&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Accounts receivable consist primarily of receivables from customers and distributors for products purchased.&amp;#160; Receivables are past due when they are unpaid greater than thirty days.&amp;#160; We determine any required reserves by considering a number of factors
 including the length of time the accounts receivable have been outstanding and our loss history.&amp;#160; We maintain an allowance for doubtful accounts for estimated losses resulting from the inability of our customers to make required payments.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Inventories&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Inventories are stated at the lower of cost (first-in
 first-out) or market.&amp;#160; We identify slow moving or obsolete inventories and estimate appropriate write-down provisions related thereto.&amp;#160; If actual market conditions are less favorable than those projected by management
 additional inventory write downs may be required.&amp;#160; In the ordinary course of business
 we manage price and supply risk of commodities by entering into various short-term purchase arrangements with our vendors.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Property and Equipment&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Property and equipment are recorded at cost.&amp;#160; Cost includes expenditures for major improvements and replacements.&amp;#160; Maintenance and repairs are charged to operations when incurred.&amp;#160; When assets are retired or otherwise disposed of
 the related costs and accumulated depreciation are removed from the appropriate accounts
 and the resulting gain or loss is recognized. &amp;#160;Depreciation expense is computed using the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the assets
 ranging from two to thirty years.&amp;#160; We capitalize certain computer software and software development costs incurred in connection with developing or obtaining computer software for internal use.&amp;#160; Capitalized software costs are included in property
 plant and equipment and amortized on a straight-line basis when placed into service over three years.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We evaluate the recoverability of property and equipment not held for sale by comparing the carrying amount of the asset or group of assets against the estimated undiscounted future cash flows expected to result from the use of the asset or group of assets and their eventual disposition
 in accordance with relevant authoritative guidance.&amp;#160; If the undiscounted future cash flows are less than the carrying value of the asset or group of assets being evaluated
 an impairment loss is recorded.&amp;#160; The loss is measured as the difference between the fair value and carrying value of the asset or group of assets being evaluated.&amp;#160; Assets to be disposed of are reported at the lower of the carrying amount or the fair value less cost to sell.&amp;#160; The estimated fair value would be based on the best information available under the circumstances
 including prices for similar assets or the results of valuation techniques
 including the present value of expected future cash flows using a discount rate commensurate with the risks involved.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Intangible Assets&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Goodwill and trademarks are reviewed for impairment annually or more frequently if impairment indicators arise.&amp;#160; Goodwill
 by reporting unit
 is required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change that more-likely-than-not reduces the fair value of a reporting unit below its carrying value.&amp;#160; We have concluded from our annual impairment testing performed in December&amp;#160;that neither of our two reporting units were at risk of failing the impairment test in the near term
 and we believe that there are no known risks for that conclusion to change at either of our reporting units.&amp;#160; Intangible assets with indefinite lives are required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change indicating that the asset might be impaired.&amp;#160; Amortizable intangible assets are amortized using the straight-line method over their estimated useful lives
 which is the estimated period over which economic benefits are expected to be provided.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Management believes that each of our trademarks has the continued ability to generate cash flows indefinitely.&amp;#160; Therefore
 each of our trademarks has been determined to have an indefinite life.&amp;#160; Management&amp;#8217;s determination that our trademarks have indefinite lives includes an evaluation of historical cash flows and projected cash flows for each of these trademarks.&amp;#160; In addition
 there are no legal
 regulatory
 contractual
 economic or other factors to limit the useful life of these trademarks.&amp;#160; Management intends to renew each of these trademarks
 which can be accomplished at little cost.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;See Note 3 &amp;#8220;Goodwill
 Trademarks and Other Intangible Assets&amp;#8221; for additional information.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Self-Insurance Reserves&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We are partially self-insured for the purposes of providing health care benefits to employees covered by our insurance plan.&amp;#160; The plan covers all full-time employees of the Company on the first day of the month after each such employee&amp;#8217;s hiring date for salaried employees
 and the first day of the month following the ninetieth day of service for hourly employees.&amp;#160; The plan covers the employees&amp;#8217; dependents
 if elected by each such employee.&amp;#160; We have contracted with an insurance carrier for stop loss coverage that commences when $100
000 in claims is paid annually for a covered participant.&amp;#160; In addition
 we have contracted for aggregate stop loss insurance
 which provides coverage after the maximum amount paid by us exceeds approximately $1.5 million.&amp;#160; Estimated unpaid claims included in accrued liabilities are $0.3 million and $0.4 million at December&amp;#160;28
 2013 and December&amp;#160;29
 2012
 respectively.&amp;#160; These amounts represent management&amp;#8217;s best estimate of amounts that have not been paid prior to the year-end dates.&amp;#160; It is reasonably possible that the actual expense we will ultimately incur could differ from such estimates.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Revenue Recognition&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;In accordance with GAAP
 we recognize operating revenues upon shipment of products to customers
 provided title and risk of loss pass to our customers.&amp;#160; In those instances where title and risk of loss does not pass until delivery
 revenue recognition is deferred until delivery has occurred.&amp;#160; In our snack products segment
 revenue for products sold through our local distribution network prior to our sale of the DSD business in November&amp;#160;2012 was recognized when the product was received by the retailer.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Provisions and allowances for sales returns
 promotional allowances
 coupon redemption and discounts are also recorded as a reduction of revenues in our consolidated financial statements.&amp;#160; These allowances are estimated based on a percentage of sales returns using historical and current market information.&amp;#160; We record certain reductions to revenue for promotional allowances.&amp;#160; There are several types of promotional allowances
 such as off-invoice allowances
 rebates and shelf space allowances.&amp;#160; An off-invoice allowance is a reduction of the sales price that is directly deducted from the invoice amount.&amp;#160; We record the amount of the deduction as a reduction to revenue when the transaction occurs.&amp;#160; We record certain allowances for coupon redemptions
 scan-back promotions and other promotional activities as a reduction to revenue.&amp;#160; Anytime we offer consideration (cash or credit) as a trade advertising or promotional allowance to a purchaser of products at any point along the distribution chain
 the amount is accrued and recorded as a reduction in revenue.&amp;#160; Costs associated with obtaining shelf space (i.e.
 &amp;#8220;slotting fees&amp;#8221;) are accounted for as a reduction of revenue in the period in which we incur such costs.&amp;#160; The accrued liabilities for these allowances are monitored throughout the time period covered by the coupon or promotion.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Selling and Administrative Expenses&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Selling and administrative expenses include salaries and wages
 bonuses and incentives
 stock-based compensation expenses
 employee related expenses
 facility-related expenses
 marketing and advertising expenses
 depreciation of property and equipment
 professional fees
 amortization of intangible assets
 provisions for losses on accounts receivable and other operating expenses.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We recorded $0.9 million
 $0.9 million and $1.0 million in fiscal years 2013
 2012 and 2011
 respectively
 for advertising costs
 which are included in selling
 general and administrative expenses on the Consolidated Statements of Operations contained herein.&amp;#160; These costs include various sponsorships
 coupon administration and consumer advertising programs that we enter into throughout the year and are expensed as incurred.&amp;#160; Our marketing programs also include selective event sponsorship designed to increase brand awareness and to provide opportunities to mass sample branded products.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Also included in selling
 general and administrative expense are costs and fees relating to the execution of in-store product demonstrations with club stores or grocery retailers
 which were $2.2 million
 $1.9 million and $3.6 million for the years ended December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 respectively.&amp;#160; The cost of product used in the demonstrations
 which is insignificant
 and the fee we pay to the independent third-party providers who conduct the in-store demonstrations
 are recorded as an expense when the event occurs.&amp;#160; Product demonstrations are conducted by independent third-party providers designated by the various retailer or club chains.&amp;#160; During the in-store demonstrations
 the consumers in the stores receive small samples of our products.&amp;#160; The consumers are not required to purchase our product in order to receive the sample.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Shipping and Handling&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Shipping and handling costs are included in cost of revenues.&amp;#160; We do not bill customers for freight.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.5in;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Income Taxes&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We account for income taxes under the asset and liability method
 which requires the recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected future tax consequences of events that have been included in the financial statements.&amp;#160; Under this method
 deferred tax assets and liabilities are determined based on the differences between the financial statements and tax basis of assets and liabilities using enacted tax rates in effect for the year in which the differences are expected to reverse.&amp;#160; The effect of a change in tax rates on deferred tax assets and liabilities is recognized in income in the period that includes the enactment date.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We record net deferred tax assets to the extent we believe these assets will more likely than not be realized.&amp;#160; In making such determination
 we consider all available positive and negative evidence
 including future reversals of existing taxable temporary differences
 projected future taxable income
 tax planning strategies and recent financial operations.&amp;#160; Failure to achieve forecasted taxable income in applicable tax jurisdictions could affect the ultimate realization of deferred tax assets and could result in an increase in our effective tax rate on future earnings.&amp;#160; A valuation allowance is provided when it is more likely than not that some portion or all of the deferred tax assets will not be realized.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;The Company uses a two-step approach to recognize and measure uncertain tax positions.&amp;#160; The first step is to evaluate the tax position for recognition by determining if the weight of available evidence indicates that it is more likely than not that the position will be sustained on audit
 including resolutions of related appeals or litigation processes
 if any.&amp;#160; The second step is to measure the tax benefit as the largest amount that is more likely than not of being realized upon ultimate settlement.&amp;#160; The Company believes that its income tax filing positions and deductions would be sustained upon examination; thus
 the Company has not recorded any uncertain tax positions as of December&amp;#160;28
 2013.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;It is our policy to recognize interest and penalties accrued on any unrecognized tax benefits as a component of income tax expense.&amp;#160; We do not have any accrued interest or penalties associated with unrecognized tax benefits for the years ended December&amp;#160;28
 2013 and December&amp;#160;29
 2012.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We file income tax returns in the U.S. federal jurisdiction and various state jurisdictions.&amp;#160; The material jurisdictions that are subject to examination by tax authorities include the U.S. federal
 Arizona
 California and Indiana.&amp;#160; Our U.S. federal income tax returns for years 2010 through 2012 remain open to examination by the Internal Revenue Service.&amp;#160; Our state tax returns for years 2009 through 2012 remain open to examination by the state jurisdictions.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Stock Options and Stock-Based Compensation&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Stock options and other stock-based compensation awards expense are adjusted for estimated forfeitures and are recognized on a straight-line basis over the requisite period of the award
 which is currently one to five years for stock options and one to three years for restricted stock.&amp;#160; We estimate future forfeiture rates based on our historical experience.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Compensation costs related to all stock-based payment arrangements
 including employee stock options
 are recognized in the financial statements based on the fair value method of accounting.&amp;#160; Excess tax benefits related to stock-based payment arrangements are classified as cash inflows from financing activities and cash outflows from operating activities.&amp;#160; See Note 9 &amp;#8220;Stockholders&amp;#8217; Equity&amp;#8221; for additional information.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Earnings Per Common Share&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Basic earnings per common share is computed by dividing net income by the weighted average number of shares of Common Stock outstanding during the period.&amp;#160; Diluted earnings per share is calculated by including all dilutive common shares such as stock options and restricted stock.&amp;#160; For the years ended December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011 options to purchase 291
571
 281
017 and 215
500 shares of our common stock
 respectively
 were excluded from the calculation of diluted earnings per share because their effects were antidilutive.&amp;#160; These exclusions were made because the options&amp;#8217; exercise prices were greater than the average market price of our Common Stock for those periods.&amp;#160; Exercises of outstanding stock options or warrants are assumed to occur for purposes of calculating diluted earnings per share for periods in which their effect would not be anti-dilutive.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: center; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=center&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Earnings per common share was computed as follows for the years ended December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011 (in thousands
 except per share data):&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 55.5%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=55%&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: -10pt; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 20pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Earnings per common share&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 2.5%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=2%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.3%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; BORDER-TOP: medium none; BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 10.7%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; BORDER-TOP: windowtext 2.25pt double; BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=10%&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: right; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;0.33&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 2.5%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=2%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.3%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; BORDER-TOP: medium none; BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 10.7%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; BORDER-TOP: windowtext 2.25pt double; BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=10%&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: right; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;0.38&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 2.5%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=2%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.3%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; BORDER-TOP: medium none; BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=BORDER-BOTTOM: windowtext 2.25pt double; BORDER-LEFT: medium none; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 10.7%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; BORDER-TOP: windowtext 2.25pt double; BORDER-RIGHT: medium none; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=10%&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: right; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=right&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;0.15&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Subsequent Events&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Subsequent events are events or transactions that occur after the balance sheet date but before financial statements are issued.&amp;#160; We recognize in the financial statements the effects of all subsequent events that provide additional evidence about conditions that existed at the date of the balance sheet
 including the estimates inherent in the process of preparing the financial statements.&amp;#160; Our financial statements do not recognize subsequent events that provide evidence about conditions that did not exist at the date of the balance sheet but arose after the balance sheet date and before financial statements are issued.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Recent Accounting Pronouncements&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;In June&amp;#160;2011
 the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&amp;#8220;FASB&amp;#8221;) issued an amendment to the existing guidance on the presentation of comprehensive income.&amp;#160; Under the amended guidance
 an entity is required to present the effect of reclassification adjustments out of accumulated other comprehensive income in both net income and other comprehensive income in the financial statements. &amp;#160;In February&amp;#160;2013
 the FASB issued an amendment to this provision
 which is effective on a prospective basis for fiscal years
 and interim periods within those years
 beginning after December&amp;#160;15
 2013.&amp;#160; We intend to adopt this guidance at the beginning of our first quarter of fiscal year 2014
 and do not anticipate any material impact on our consolidated financial statements and related disclosures.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;In July&amp;#160;2013
 the FASB issued accounting guidance on the financial statement presentation of an unrecognized tax benefit when a net operating loss carryforward
 a similar tax loss or a tax credit carryforward exists.&amp;#160; The guidance is effective prospectively for fiscal years
 and interim periods within those years
 beginning after December&amp;#160;15
 2013
 with an option for early adoption.&amp;#160; We intend to adopt this guidance at the beginning of our first quarter of fiscal year 2014
 and do not anticipate any material impact on our consolidated financial statements and related disclosures.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;3.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt; &lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Goodwill

&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Goodwill and trademarks are reviewed for impairment annually in the fourth fiscal quarter
 or more frequently if impairment indicators arise.&amp;#160; Goodwill is required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change that more-likely-than-not reduces the fair value of a reporting unit below its carrying value.&amp;#160; Intangible assets with indefinite lives are required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change indicating that the asset might be impaired.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.44%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=1%&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;To fund the acquisition of Fresh Frozen Foods
 we entered into a $60.0&amp;#160;million senior secured term loan and a new $30.0 million senior secured revolving line of credit with a syndicate of lenders led by U.S. Bank National Association (&amp;#8220;U.S. Bank&amp;#8221;)
 pursuant to a Credit Agreement
 a Security Agreement and certain other customary ancillary agreements (the &amp;#8220;Senior Credit Facility&amp;#8221;).&amp;#160; To facilitate the Senior Credit Facility
 the Company and its wholly owned subsidiaries entered into a Letter Amendment Agreement
 dated as of November&amp;#160;8
 2013
 with U.S. Bank National Association (the &amp;#8220;Letter Amendment&amp;#8221;).&amp;#160; The Letter Amendment reconciled the terms of Senior Credit Facility with the terms of the Loan and Security Agreement and that certain Loan Agreement (Term Loan)
 dated as of November&amp;#160;30
 2006
 by and between the Company&amp;#8217;s wholly owned subsidiary
 La Cometa Properties
&amp;#160;Inc.
 and U.S. Bank.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;The borrowing capacity available to us under the Senior Credit Facility consists of notes representing:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.75in;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Symbol; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;&amp;#183;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt; size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;A revolving line of credit up to $30.0 million maturing on November 8
 2018.&amp;#160; Based on the maximum permitted leverage ratio as of December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 the Company&amp;#8217;s debt balance that could have been outstanding under our line of credit was reduced from the maximum borrowing capacity of $30.0 million to $8.4 million
 of which $3.2 million was outstanding at December&amp;#160;28
 2013.&amp;#160; All borrowings under the revolving line of credit bear interest at either (i)&amp;#160;the prime rate of interest announced by U.S. Bank from time to time or (ii)&amp;#160;LIBOR
 plus the LIBOR Rate Margin (as defined in the revolving credit facility note as adjusted.)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.75in;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.75in;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Symbol; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;&amp;#183;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt; size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;An equipment term loan B due September&amp;#160;2020 with interest at 3.12%.&amp;#160; On August&amp;#160;14
 2013
 we entered into an equipment term loan B to finance equipment located at Willamette Valley Fruit Company.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.75in;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;The Senior Credit Facility maintained the terms and borrowing capacity of the prior agreement with respect to the following:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.75in;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Symbol; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;&amp;#183;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt; size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Bluffton
&amp;#160;Indiana mortgage loan due December&amp;#160;2016; interest rate at 30 day LIBOR&amp;#160;plus 165 basis points
 fixed through a swap agreement to 6.85%; collateralized by land and building in Bluffton
&amp;#160;Indiana.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.75in;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.75in;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Symbol; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;&amp;#183;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt; size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Lynden
 Washington real estate term loan due July&amp;#160;2017; interest at LIBOR plus 165 basis&amp;#160;points; fixed through a swap agreement to 4.28%; secured by a leasehold interest in the real property in Lynden
 Washington.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: -0.25in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt 0.75in;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;As is customary in such financings
 U.S. Bank
 on behalf of the syndicate of lenders
 may terminate the syndicate&amp;#8217;s commitments
 accelerate the repayment of amounts outstanding and exercise other remedies upon the occurrence of an event of default (as defined in the Senior Credit Facility)
 subject
 in certain instances
 to the expiration of an applicable cure period.&amp;#160; The Senior Credit Facility requires us to maintain compliance with certain financial covenants
 including a minimum fixed charge coverage ratio and a leverage ratio.&amp;#160; At December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 we were in compliance with all of the financial covenants.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: center; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=center&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Net interest expense consisted of the following for the fiscal years ended December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011 (in thousands):&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 3.56%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-TOP: 0in; valign=bottom width=3%&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: center; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=center&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;

&lt;td style=PADDING-BOTTOM: 2.25pt; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; WIDTH: 1.44%; PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; BACKGROUND: #cceeff; PADDING-TOP: 0in; bgcolor=#CCEEFF valign=bottom width=1%&gt;

&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: center; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=center&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Interest Rate Swaps&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: center; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=center&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;To manage exposure to changing interest rates
 we selectively enter into interest rate swap agreements.&amp;#160; Our interest rate swaps qualify for and are designated as cash flow hedges.&amp;#160; Changes in the fair value of a swap that is highly effective and that is designated and qualifies as a cash flow hedge to the extent that the hedge is effective
 are recorded in other comprehensive income (loss).&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: center; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=center&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We entered into an interest rate swap in 2006 to convert the interest rate of the mortgage to purchase the Bluffton
&amp;#160;Indiana plant from the contractual rate of 30 day LIBOR plus 165 basis points to a fixed rate of 6.85%.&amp;#160; The swap has a fixed pay-rate of 6.85% and a notional value of approximately $1.9 million and $2.0 million at December&amp;#160;28
 2013 and December&amp;#160;29
 2012
 respectively
 and expires in December&amp;#160;2016.&amp;#160; We evaluate the effectiveness of the hedge on a quarterly basis and
 at December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 the hedge is highly effective.&amp;#160; The interest rate swap had a fair value of $239
841 and $343
710 at December&amp;#160;28
 2013 and December&amp;#160;29
 2012
 respectively
 which were recorded as a liability on the accompanying Consolidated Balance Sheets.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The swap value was determined in accordance with the fair value measurement guidance discussed earlier using Level 2 observable inputs and approximates the loss that would have been realized if the contract had been settled at the end of the fiscal period.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: center; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=center&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;We entered into another interest rate swap in January&amp;#160;2008 to effectively convert the interest rate on the real estate term loan to a fixed rate of 4.28%.&amp;#160; The interest rate swap is structured with decreasing notional values to match the expected pay down of the debt.&amp;#160; The notional value of the swap was $2.8 million and $3.0 million at December&amp;#160;28
 2013 and December&amp;#160;29
 2012
 respectively.&amp;#160; The interest rate swap is accounted for as a cash flow hedge derivative and expires in July&amp;#160;2017.&amp;#160; We evaluate the effectiveness of the hedge on a quarterly basis and
 at December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 the hedge is highly effective. &amp;#160;The interest rate swap had fair value of $286
228 and $422
508 at December&amp;#160;28
 2013 and December&amp;#160;29
 2012
 respectively
 which were recorded as a liability on the accompanying Consolidated Balance Sheet.&amp;#160; This value was determined in accordance with the fair value measurement guidance discussed earlier using Level 2 observable inputs and approximates the loss that would have been realized if the contract had been settled at the end of the fiscal period.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;8.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 3pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=1&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt; &lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Commitments and Contingencies&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: center; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=center&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;Our future contractual obligations consist principally of long-term debt
 operating leases
 minimum commitments regarding third-party warehouse operations services
 forward purchase agreements and remaining minimum royalty payments due licensors pursuant to brand licensing agreements.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: center; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=center&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; size=2&gt;Leases&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-ALIGN: center; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt; align=center&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=TEXT-INDENT: 0.5in; MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; size=2&gt;During the years ended December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 December&amp;#160;29
 2012 and December&amp;#160;31
 2011
 the rental expense from operating leases was $1.8 million
 $1.6 million and $1.7 million
 respectively.&amp;#160; As of December&amp;#160;28
 2013
 minimum rental commitments under non-cancellable operating leases were (in thousands):&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
